739. impune, ‘sasely.'

750-3. These three lines refer to the story of Glaucus, the son of the Cretan king Minos, who was drowned in a honey-cask. Minos ordered the Argive seer Polyidus to raise him to life, and being unable he was shut up in the vault with the body. A snake glided to the body, and Polyidus killed it. Presently came another snake and dropped a herb on its dead companion, which revived. Polyidus then covered Glaucus with the herb, and revived him.
